{"title_page": "Deveronvale F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Deveronvale\n| image    = Deveronvalebadge.png\n| fullname = Deveronvale Football Club\n| nickname = ''Vale''\n| founded  = 1938\n| ground   = [[Princess Royal Park, Banff|Princess Royal Park]], [[Banff, Aberdeenshire|Banff]]\n| capacity = 2,600 (360 seated)\n| chairman = Jim Mair\n| manager  = Steve Dolan\n| league   = {{Scottish football updater|Deveronv}}\n| season      = {{Scottish football updater|Deveronv2}}\n| position    = {{Scottish football updater|Deveronv3}}\n| pattern_la1 = _cork18a\n| pattern_b1  = _cork18a\n| pattern_ra1 = _cork18a\n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = _color_3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1    = FF0000\n| body1       = FF0000\n| rightarm1   = FF0000\n| shorts1     = FF0000\n| socks1      = FF0000\n| pattern_la2 = _whiteborder\n| pattern_b2  = _accrington1819a\n| pattern_ra2 = _whiteborder\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2    = 89CFF0\n| body2       = 89CFF0\n| rightarm2   = 89CFF0\n| shorts2     = FFFFFF\n| socks2      = 89CFF0\n}}\n\n'''Deveronvale Football Club''' are senior [[association football]] club currently playing the [[Highland Football League]] in [[Scotland]]. They were founded in 1938 and play their football at the [[Princess Royal Park, Banff|Princess Royal Park]] in the town of [[Banff, Aberdeenshire|Banff]], (formerly [[Banffshire]], now officially [[Aberdeenshire]]), [[Scotland]].\n\nThe club was formed in 1938 when Deveron Valley and Banff Rovers joined together. The name comes from the [[River Deveron]], which has its mouth at Banff.\n\nAfter they were formed, it took them one year to get into the Highland League. In August 1939, Deveronvale played their first league game. Their first win came a month later. In 1948 Deveronvale signed James \u2018Jimmy\u2019 Williamson from Dunipace Juniors, Jimmy would go on to play for Deveronvale for 7 years and in the process set the record for highest number of individual goals In the highland league at 197 goals. The crest of Deveronvale FC was designed during the early 1970s by local school teacher, Mr. Chris Murray. He chose a 'heraldic' seagull to represent the twin fishing towns of Banff and Macduff.\n\nIn 2003 the Vale won the Highland League title for the first time in their history and repeated this feat once more three years later.\n\nDue to them being a senior team, they can play in the [[Scottish Cup]]. In the [[2006\u201307 in Scottish football|2006\u201307 season]], Deveronvale made it into the fourth round of the Scottish Cup after a 5\u20134 defeat of [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Third Division]] side [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]], before going out at home to [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]] side [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/6325369.stm Deveronvale target more cup glory], ''BBC Sport'', 2 February 2007, Accessed 3 June 2008</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/6322675.stm Deveronvale 0\u20131 Partick Thistle], ''BBC Sport'', 3 February 2007, Accessed 3 June 2008</ref>\n\nIn the [[2011\u201312 in Scottish football|2011\u201312 season]], Deveronvale entered the [[2011\u201312 Scottish Challenge Cup|Scottish Challenge Cup]] for the first time.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13671944.stm Highland duo enter new Ramsdens Cup], ''BBC Sport'', 6 June 2011, Accessed 6 June 2011</ref>\n\nThe club celebrated its 80th anniversary in the 2018-19 season.\n\n==Current squad==\n{{updated|7 January 2019}}\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=GK|name=James Blanchard}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=GK|name=Grant Pennet}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=Kevin Adams}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=Ross Aitken}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=Robbie Allan}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=Lewis Dunbar}}\n{{Fs