{"title_page": "Temperate forest", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Temperate forest''' is a [[forest]] found between the [[Tropical Rainforest|tropical]] and [[Taiga|boreal]] regions, located in the [[temperate climate|temperate zone]]. It is within the second largest biome on the planet, covering 25%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalforestatlas.yale.edu/temperate-zone|title=Forest Regions Temperate Zone|work=Yale School of Forestry and Environmental Studies|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> of the world's forest area, only behind the [[boreal forest]], which covers about 33%. These forests cover both hemispheres at latitudes ranging from 25 to 50 degrees<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/temperate-forest|title=Temperate forest|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>, wrapping the planet in a belt similar to that of the boreal forest. Due to its large size spanning several continents, there are several main types: [[Temperate deciduous forest|deciduous]], [[Temperate coniferous forest|coniferous]], [[Temperate broadleaf and mixed forest|broadleaf and mixed forest]] and [[Temperate rainforest|rainforest]].\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate of a temperate forest is highly variable depending on the location of the forest. For example, [[Los Angeles]] and [[Vancouver|Vancouver, Canada]] are both considered to be located in a temperate zone, however, Vancouver is located in a temperate rainforest, while Los Angeles is more subtropical. Temperate forests typically have winters that often reach below freezing, however even this is not always true. The [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] [[deciduous forests]] retain their deciduous nature largely due to the excessive freezing days each winter,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/temperate-forest/Environment|title=Environment of the Temperate forest|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> as the leaves often freeze over and are only designed to live for one season. Milder areas such as the southern coast of [[British Columbia]] where the average winter lows are above freezing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=889&lang=e&StationName=Vancouver&SearchType=Contains&stnNameSubmit=go&dCode=1|title=Canadian Climate Normals 1981-2010 Station Data|work=Environment Canada|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> often have [[evergreen]] [[rainforests]].\n\nHey guess what, nobody cares about your school work!!!\n\n==Effect of human activity==\nTemperate forests are located in the middle latitudes where much of the planet's population is. Not only were these forests cut down to build cities (i.e. [[New York City]] and [[Seattle]]), they have also been \"cut down long ago to make way for cultivation.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=de Rothschild|first=David|date=2008-05-19|title=Earth Matters|url=https://archive.org/details/earthmatters00roth|url-access=registration|publisher=DK Children}}</ref> This biome has been subject to [[mining]], [[logging]], [[hunting]], [[pollution]], [[deforestation]] and [[habitat loss]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sciencing.com/human-influences-temperate-rainforest-8480768.html|title=Human Influences on the Temperate Rainforest|work=Sciencing|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a [[direct quote]] from the book \"Earth Matters\" by [[David Mayer de Rothschild]]: \"Deciduous forests have been more affected by human activity than any other [[biome]], since they grow in the areas of fertile soil and relatively gentle climate that are most popular for humans to live in. Huge areas, especially in China and Europe, were cut down long ago to make way for cultivation. Most existing deciduous forest is regrown (\"secondary forest\"), and only tiny fragments of original forest remain.\"\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Forest]]\n* [[Temperate broadleaf and mixed forests]]\n* [[Temperate coniferous forest]]\n* [[Temperate deciduous forest]]\n* [[Temperate rainforest]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Biomes]]\n[[Category:Ecosystems]]\n[[Category:Forests]]\n\n\n{{ecology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Temperate forest''' is a [[forest]] found between the [[Tropical Rainforest|tropical]] and [[Taiga|boreal]] regions, located in the [[temperate climate|temperate zone]]. It is within the second largest biome on the planet, covering 25%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalforestatlas.yale.edu/temperate-zone|title=Forest Regions Temperate Zone|work=Yale School of Forestry and Environmental Studies|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> of the world's forest area, only behind the [[boreal forest]], which covers about 33%. These forests cover both hemispheres at latitudes ranging from 25 to 50 degrees<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/temperate-forest|title=Temperate forest|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>, wrapping the planet in a belt similar to that of the boreal forest. Due to its large size spanning several continents, there are several main types: [[Temperate deciduous forest|deciduous]], [[Temperate coniferous forest|coniferous]], [[Temperate broadleaf and mixed forest|broadleaf and mixed forest]] and [[Temperate rainforest|rainforest]].\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate of a temperate forest is highly variable depending on the location of the forest. For example, [[Los Angeles]] and [[Vancouver|Vancouver, Canada]] are both considered to be located in a temperate zone, however, Vancouver is located in a temperate rainforest, while Los Angeles is more subtropical. Temperate forests typically have winters that often reach below freezing, however even this is not always true. The [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] [[deciduous forests]] retain their deciduous nature largely due to the excessive freezing days each winter,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/temperate-forest/Environment|title=Environment of the Temperate forest|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> as the leaves often freeze over and are only designed to live for one season. Milder areas such as the southern coast of [[British Columbia]] where the average winter lows are above freezing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=889&lang=e&StationName=Vancouver&SearchType=Contains&stnNameSubmit=go&dCode=1|title=Canadian Climate Normals 1981-2010 Station Data|work=Environment Canada|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> often have [[evergreen]] [[rainforests]].\n\n==Types of temperate forests==\n===Deciduous===\n{{main|Temperate deciduous forest}}\n\nThey are found in Europe, East Asia, North America and in some parts of South America.\nDeciduous forests are composed mainly of [[broadleaf tree]]s, such as maple and oak, that shed all their leaves during one season.<ref>{{Cite web | author= Basic Biology | date= 2016 | title= Forest | url=https://basicbiology.net/environment/land/forest}}</ref> They are typically found in three middle-latitude regions with temperate climates characterized by a winter season and year-round precipitation: eastern [[North America]], western [[Eurasia]] and northeastern [[Asia]].<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/science/deciduous-forest \"deciduous forest\"], \"[[Encyclopaedia Britannica]]\", Retrieved on 2019-02-20. </ref>\n\n===Coniferous===\n{{main|Temperate coniferous forest}}\nConiferous forests are composed of needle-leaved evergreen trees, such as pine or fir. Evergreen forests are typically found in regions with moderate climates.  [[Taiga|Boreal forests]], however, are an exception as they are found in subarctic regions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/temperate-forest|title=Temperate forest {{!}} ecology|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en}}</ref> Coniferous trees often have an advantage over broadleaf trees in harsher environments. Their leaves are typically hardier and longer lived but require more energy to grow.\n\n===Broadleaf and mixed===\n{{main|Temperate broadleaf and mixed forest}}\nAs the name implies, conifers and broadleaf trees grow in the same area. The main trees found in these forests are the great redwood, oak, ash, maple, birch, beech, poplar, elm and pine. Hardwood evergreen trees which are widely spaced and are found in the Mediterranean region are olive, cork, oak and stone pine.\n\n=== Rainforest ===\n{{Main|Temperate rainforest}}\nTemperate rainforests are the wettest of all the types, and are found only in very wet coastal areas. Trees here are all evergreens, and are typically covered with thick [[moss]] and [[underbrush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/olym/learn/nature/temperate-rain-forests.htm|title=Temperate Rain Forests|work=NPS|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> Adding to its rarity is that most of the temperate rainforests outside of protected areas have been cut down and no longer exist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/olym/learn/nature/temperate-rain-forests.htm|title=Temperate Rain Forests|work=NPS|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> Currently, complete temperate rainforests can only be found in select areas of the [[Pacific Northwest]] and parts of [[Chile]] and [[New Zealand]]. Small stands can be found in [[Great Britain]] and southern [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eartheclipse.com/ecosystem/temperate-rainforest-biome.html|title=Temperate Rainforest Biome Location|work=Earth Eclipse|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\n==Effect of human activity==\nTemperate forests are located in the middle latitudes where much of the planet's population is. Not only were these forests cut down to build cities (i.e. [[New York City]] and [[Seattle]]), they have also been \"cut down long ago to make way for cultivation.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=de Rothschild|first=David|date=2008-05-19|title=Earth Matters|url=https://archive.org/details/earthmatters00roth|url-access=registration|publisher=DK Children}}</ref> This biome has been subject to [[mining]], [[logging]], [[hunting]], [[pollution]], [[deforestation]] and [[habitat loss]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sciencing.com/human-influences-temperate-rainforest-8480768.html|title=Human Influences on the Temperate Rainforest|work=Sciencing|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a [[direct quote]] from the book \"Earth Matters\" by [[David Mayer de Rothschild]]: \"Deciduous forests have been more affected by human activity than any other [[biome]], since they grow in the areas of fertile soil and relatively gentle climate that are most popular for humans to live in. Huge areas, especially in China and Europe, were cut down long ago to make way for cultivation. Most existing deciduous forest is regrown (\"secondary forest\"), and only tiny fragments of original forest remain.\"\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Forest]]\n* [[Temperate broadleaf and mixed forests]]\n* [[Temperate coniferous forest]]\n* [[Temperate deciduous forest]]\n* [[Temperate rainforest]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Biomes]]\n[[Category:Ecosystems]]\n[[Category:Forests]]\n\n\n{{ecology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2601:8c:c001:9820:cdc8:2267:c8ab:4ee6", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Joe Mama)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperate_forest"}
{"title_page": "Carol A. Barnes", "text_new": "{{For|the British broadcaster|Carol Barnes}}\n{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Carol A. Barnes\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = United States\n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Neuroscience]], [[memory]], [[learning]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Arizona]]\n| alma_mater = B.A., [[University of California, Riverside]] <br />\nM.A., [[University of Ottawa]] <br />Ph.D. [[Carleton University]] <br />postdoctoral training in neurophysiology at [[Dalhousie University]], [[University of Oslo]], and the Cerebral Functions Group at [[University College London]] \n| doctoral_advisor = Peter Fried\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Carol_A_Barnes.png|thumb|Carol A Barnes, PhD]]\n'''Carol A. Barnes, Ph.D.''' is a [[neuroscientist]] and a Regents' [[Professor]] of [[psychology]] at the [[University of Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol |title=Carol Barnes |publisher=Department of Psychology, University of Arizona |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525213406/http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since 2006, she has been the Evelyn F. McKnight Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |title=Evelyn F. McKnight Endowed Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date=2006-12-11 |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919034703/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |archive-date=2013-09-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and is director of the Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |title=McKnight Brain Institute at the University of Arizona |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195119/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barnes has been president of the [[Society for Neuroscience]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfn.org/about/volunteer-leadership/sfn-presidents |title=Society for Neuroscience - SfN Presidents |publisher=Society for Neuroscience |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> and is a [[Fellow of the AAAS|Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V |title=Fellows &#124; AAAS MemberCentral |publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525202502/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and foreign member of the [[Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |title=Utenlandske medlemmer naturvitenskapelig klass |publisher=Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters |accessdate=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222003839/http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |archivedate=2013-12-22 }}</ref> She was elected to the [[National Academy of Sciences]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasonline.org/news-and-multimedia/news/May-1-2018-NAS-Election.html|title=May 1 2018 NAS Election|first=National Academy of Sciences -|last=http://www.nasonline.org|website=www.nasonline.org}}</ref>\n\nBarnes has produced over 170 peer reviewed publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gruberprizes.org/SelectingRecipients/SelectionAdvisoryBoard_Bio.php?id=23 |title=The Gruber Foundation Homepage &#124; The Gruber Foundation |publisher=Gruberprizes.org |date=2014-03-03 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> Broadly, her research is focused on the neurophysiological and behavioral changes that occur in the brain during aging. Understanding of these changes may shed light on the processes that contribute to age-related neurodegenerative disorders such as [[Alzheimer's Disease]]. Barnes also developed the [[Barnes maze]], a spatial navigation memory task that is used to assess hippocampal-dependent memory.\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:Carleton_University_River.jpg|thumb|Carleton University River]]\n[[File:Riverside,_California_view_from_Box_Springs.jpg|thumb|Riverside, California view from Box Springs]]\n[[File:The_University_of_Oslo.jpg|thumb|The University of Oslo]]\n[[File:London_MMB_08_University_College.jpg|thumb|London MMB 08 University College]]\nCarol Barnes received a Bachelors of Arts in Psychology with honors at the [[University of California]], riverside, in 1971. She continued her education at [[Carleton University]] located in Ottawa Ontario, Canada, earning her Masters of Arts degree in Psychology in 1972.During her studies in pursuing a PhD in Psychology, Barnes took a temporary position as a postdoctoral researcher researching in [[neuropsychology]] and [[neurophysiology]] in the department of psychology at [[Dalhousie University]], at the institute of neurophysiology of [[University of Oslo]]as well as in Cerebral function at [[University College London|University College of London]]. In 1977 she graduated with Cum Laude in psychology at [[Carleton University]].\n\n== Career ==\nBarnes currently holds the positions of director for two organizations The Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute and the Neural Systems-Memory and Aging. She holds the position of the Endowed Chair of the Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute for Learning-Memory in Aging. Today she is a regents professor at the [[University of Arizona]] in Tucson, Arizona. Barnes is apart\u00a0of the BIO5 Institute that is funded by the Technology and Research Fund (TRIF).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bio5.org/about/why|title=Why BIO5 {{!}} BIO5 Institute|website=bio5.org|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> At the BIO5 institute she works with students addressing [[Alzheimer's disease]] and other age-related brain diseases. Barnes also teaches cancer biology, neuroscience, psychology, and physiological sciences.\n\n== Research ==\nBarnes is involved with the [[neuroscience]] research community on a national and local level. Barnes research spans through 4 decades aiming to better understand the aging of the brain in relation to cognitive diseases. Her research is conducted by utilizing animal models such as primates and rats to explore and understand how memory is impacted through the normal aging process of the brain through means of neurobiological mechanisms that are involved. The use of animal models in Barnes research is translated into treatments used for abnormal functioning of the brain aimed at prolonging the cognitive lifespan of older individuals. The nature of Barnes research entails the use of behavioral, anatomical, [[Electrophysiology|electrophysiological]] and molecular techniques\u00a0 to further examine the implications of normal aging impacting brain functioning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.arizona.edu/users/carol-barnes|title=Carol Barnes {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.arizona.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Most areas of her research involves examining and observing the [[hippocampus]] structure in the brains of rats and monkeys, observing and recording\u00a0 synaptic transmission in cell to cell signaling, and genomic sequencing.\n\n=== [[Barnes maze|Barnes Maze]] ===\nTo study spatial learning and memory, Carol Barnes created her own maze to test whether rodents, specifically mice, could remember the location of an escape box on a platform. This test has become a standard method of memory testing in laboratories. Designed in 1979, Barnes' maze was an alternative to study memory without the use of external reward or punishment, while also reducing the stress put on the animal throughout the process.\n[[File:Barnes_maze.jpg|thumb|The Barnes maze]]\nThe original study consisted of a platform (122&nbsp;cm diameter) raised 91&nbsp;cm above the floor with 18 circular holes (9.5&nbsp;cm diameters) spaced evenly around the perimeter. Under one of the holes is a black escape box, or any dark color in contrast to the color of the platform; the rest of the holes lead to false escape boxes. The study consisted of 3 variations of the experiment. First, the mouse simply had to find the escape chamber that was placed under one of the holes. Second, the escape chamber was moved to a hole rotated 120-140 degrees from the original hole; the original hole was also covered. Third, the same method as the second variation was used except the original hole was not covered. Barnes and her team found that overall, male mice performed better in all variations of the experiment. Further, they found younger mice also performed better in all variations, while older mice demonstrated notable difficulties in variations 2 and 3. This showed aging impairment in spatial memory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gawel|first=Kinga|last2=Gibula|first2=Ewa|last3=Marszalek-Grabska|first3=Marta|last4=Filarowska|first4=Joanna|last5=Kotlinska|first5=Jolanta H.|date=2019-01-01|title=Assessment of spatial learning and memory in the Barnes maze task in rodents\u2014methodological consideration|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|journal=Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Archives of Pharmacology|language=en|volume=392|issue=1|pages=1\u201318|doi=10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|issn=1432-1912|pmc=6311199|pmid=30470917}}</ref>\n[[File:Hippocampus.png|thumb|Hippocampus]]\nSpatial memory corresponds to the functioning of the [[hippocampus]], while route learning involves the [[Striatum|striatal]] systems. Overall, rodents of various ages learned T-mazes within the same number of trials, but the strategies used to learn and remember mazes differed with age. Young rats predominately utilized \u201cplace\u201d strategies which rely upon [[Hippocampus|hippocampal]] functioning, while older rats relied upon \u201cresponse\u201d strategies. Using [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] imaging techniques, Barnes and her team were able to see that in normally aged brains of rodents, the size of the [[hippocampus]] did not change while the volume of [[Grey matter|cortical grey matter]] did. This animal model allowed an understanding of what the brain looks like during normal human functioning to compare it to brains that have been degenerated due to [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]] (rodents do not exhibit AD). These findings demonstrate that while during normal aging the [[hippocampus]] remains the same size, its function may decrease in comparison to functions of other areas of the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Samson|first=Rachel D.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2013|title=Impact of Aging Brain Circuits on Cognition|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3694726/|journal=The European journal of neuroscience|volume=37|issue=12|pages=1903\u20131915|doi=10.1111/ejn.12183|issn=0953-816X|pmc=3694726|pmid=23773059|via=}}</ref>\n\nLooking deeper into the tissue affected, single-cell imaging showed there were 3 main types of cells that make up the hippocampus. When observing cell activity and the number of cells of the hippocampus of rats, it was found that the [[CA1 neuron|CA1]] and [[CA3 region|CA3]] [[pyramidal cell]]s continued to be active and of the same volume. However, the number of [[granule cell]]s of the [[dentate gyrus]] continuously decreased with age; the function of these cells also declined leading Carol and her team to conclude these gyrus cells are the weak link of the hippocampal circuit involved in memory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barnes|first=Carol A.|date=2011-10-03|title=Secrets of aging: What does a normally aging brain look like?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3186042/|journal=F1000 Biology Reports|volume=3|doi=10.3410/B3-22|issn=1757-594X|pmc=3186042|pmid=22003369}}</ref>\n\nA few of Barnes\u2019s latest research publication was published in 2017 are:\u00a0 \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S016643281630420X Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in the macaque monkeys]\u201d, \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28174334 Evidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus]\u201d, and \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627317305615 The aging navigational system]\u201d.\n\n=== Primate Research ===\n[[File:Brain_regions_involved_in_memory_formation.jpg|thumb|Brain regions involved in memory formation]]\nIn addition to work on rodent models, Dr. Barnes has helped advance the field of normative aging research using nonhuman primate models, specifically [[Macaque|macaque monkeys]].\u00a0 Primarily, Barnes\u2019 early work in macaques helped to tie together neurobiological data collected from rodents and functional imaging data from older humans. In the paper \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4848213/ Memory impairment in aged primates is associated with region-specific network dysfunction]\u201d Barnes and her team showed that older monkeys had significant impairment on object recognition than younger monkeys. In addition, the older monkeys displayed a lower density of inhibitory somatostatin positive [[interneuron]]s in the [[CA3 region|CA3]] sub-region of the [[hippocampus]]. These [[interneuron]]s are responsible for regulating the activity of excitatory neurons in the [[hippocampus]]. With less [[interneuron]] density, the baseline firing rate of [[CA3 region|CA3]] excitatory neurons was elevated, which resembles the increased hippocampal activity shown in imaging studies of older human adults. Both a decrease in [[interneuron]] density and increase baseline firing rates in the [[hippocampus]] have been associated with poor cognition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2019-12-26|title=Experiments in macaque monkeys provide critical insights into age-associated changes in cognitive and sensory function|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6936691/|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=116|issue=52|pages=26247\u201326254|doi=10.1073/pnas.1902279116|issn=0027-8424|pmc=6936691|pmid=31871147}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in the paper \u201cEvidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus\u201d Dr. Barnes and her team found evidence that mammals require the same quantity of neurons in the hippocampus to encode memory of a single experience. This finding means that the studied rodents, nonhuman primates, and humans all use a stable amount of neurons to encode a similar virtual experience. However, since all three subjects have different sized hippocampi, the proportion of neurons used for the encoding of experience differ. Rodents have the smallest hippocampus and thus use 40% of their hippocampus neurons for encoding, nonhuman primates have larger hippocampi and use 4%, and finally humans have the largest hippocampi and use an estimated 2.5% for experiential encoding.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wixted|first=John T.|last2=Goldinger|first2=Stephen D.|last3=Squire|first3=Larry R.|last4=Kuhn|first4=Joel R.|last5=Papesh|first5=Megan H.|last6=Smith|first6=Kris A.|last7=Treiman|first7=David M.|last8=Steinmetz|first8=Peter N.|date=2018-01-30|title=Coding of episodic memory in the human hippocampus|url=https://www.pnas.org/content/115/5/1093|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=115|issue=5|pages=1093\u20131098|doi=10.1073/pnas.1716443115|issn=0027-8424|pmid=29339476|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nDr. Barnes has also done research to see how executive function changes with normative aging. [[Executive functions]] are the higher order process humans take part in such as attention, decision making, impulse control, and emotional control. Once again studying [[macaque]]s, Barnes and her team focused on two aspects of executive function, attentional monitoring and updating as well as set shifting. Attentional monitoring and updating are when the rules of a given situation change requiring a corresponding change in behavioral responses. For example, when two options are presented one is the correct initial choice. When the correct choice becomes the second option instead, attentional monitoring and updating help correct for the rule change and alter behavior. The change in behavior is mediated through a process of trial and error which helps associate desired outcomes with certain behaviors. Barnes and her team found that older monkeys needed a greater number of trials to accurately account for a rule change. Meaning, the executive system behind attentional monitoring and updating is impaired with aging. Secondly, [[Cognitive flexibility|set shifting]] is the ability to unconsciously shift attention between tasks while maintaining accuracy. In her research, Barnes presented macaque monkeys with an object recognition test of previously learned objects. She then presented interfering objects which required shifts between the object choice and evaluation of novel objects. Her results showed that older monkeys performed better on object recognition with interference than younger monkeys. Thus set shifting abilities seem to be maintained if not enhanced with aging. The most important discovery out of these studies, however, is that the two aspects of executive function, monitoring and updating and set shifting, were shown to be independent systems that are affected differently with age.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Smith|first2=Anne C.|last3=Burke|first3=Sara N.|last4=Gazzaley|first4=Adam|last5=Barnes|first5=Carol A.|date=2017-03-30|title=Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in macaque monkeys|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5493156/|journal=Behavioural brain research|volume=322|issue=Pt B|pages=329\u2013338|doi=10.1016/j.bbr.2016.06.056|issn=0166-4328|pmc=5493156|pmid=27368416}}</ref>\n\nA final research contribution of Carol A Barnes involves the study of spatial networks and spatial memories in aging [[macaque]]s. Barnes and her team studied brain activity in four different conditions for movement: cages, sitting, walking on a treadmill, and freely walking around space. The study found that younger macaques have distinct spatial networks for all four distinct conditions. However, older monkeys displayed less differentiated activity of spatial networks. Meaning, all conditions evoked activation of the same undifferentiated networks. This finding suggests dynamic network changes as a possible explanation for spatial cognition deficits. In other words, the spatial processing networks become less precise with age and may contribute to spatial memory loss or confusion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Engle|first=James R.|last2=Machado|first2=Christopher J.|last3=Permenter|first3=Michele R.|last4=Vogt|first4=Julie A.|last5=Maurer|first5=Andrew P.|last6=Bulleri|first6=Alicia M.|last7=Barnes|first7=Carol A.|date=2016-11-30|title=Network Patterns Associated with Navigation Behaviors Are Altered in Aged Nonhuman Primates|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/36/48/12217|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=36|issue=48|pages=12217\u201312227|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4116-15.2016|issn=0270-6474|pmid=27903730|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nBarnes interest of normative aging in the brain stems from her grandfather when she and her family noticed that his memory was declining.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sherva|first=Kara|date=2015|title=Carol Barnes: A Prominent Voice in the Neuroscience of Aging, and a Proponent of Women in Neuroscience|url=https://soundideas.pugetsound.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=soundneuroscience|journal=Sound Neuroscience: An Undergraduate Neuroscience Journal|volume=2|pages=|via=}}</ref> Furthermore, Barnes is included in the [https://neurotree.org/beta/tree.php?pid=547 Neuroscience Academic Family Tree] . Listed there are her mentors and mentees.\n\n== Supporting Women and the Underprivileged in Neuroscience ==\nCarol A Barnes has been lauded by her peers and the public for her outstanding work in promoting opportunities for women and the underprivileged in neuroscience. In 2010, she received the Mika Salpeter Lifetime Achievement Award<ref name=\":0\" /> which \u201crecognizes individuals with outstanding career achievements in neuroscience who have also actively promoted the professional advancement of women in neuroscience.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfn.org/initiatives/awards|title=Awards|website=www.sfn.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore she is an active participant in the [https://msrp.medicine.arizona.edu/programs/disadvantaged-high-school-student-research-program NIH Disadvantaged High School Student Research Program], [https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/pa-files/PAR-99-091.html Minority Access to Research Careers], and the [https://mcnair.njit.edu/ McNair Achievement Program]. Finally, in 2013 Barnes gave a keynote address at the [https://www.sfn.org/cwinrsvp Celebration of Women in Neuroscience] entitled \u201cThe Evolving Face of Neuroscience: Role of Women and Globalization.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and Honors: ==\n{{external|section|date=April 2020}}\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://embi.arizona.edu/barnes/honors-awards|title=Dr. Carol A. Barnes - Honors and Awards {{!}} Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute|website=embi.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/funding/education.jsp?fund_type=1 National science Foundation Summer Research Fellowship], 1969\n** This fellowship funds students or identity programs that are focused on education developments\n* [https://osap.gov.on.ca/OSAPPortal/en/A-ZListofAid/PRDR019245.html Ontario Graduate Fellowship], 1972\u201374\n** For students pursuing their graduate studies at Master\u2019s and doctoral levels. This is a merit-based scholarship for students a part of the Ontario Graduate program.\n* [https://www.nlm.nih.gov/ep/NRSAFellowshipGrants.html NIH National Research Service Award], 1979\u201381\n** For Postdoctoral students gaining research and clinical training in both MD/PhD or other dual-doctoral degree training program\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/pubs/2002/nsf02178/nsf02178.htm NATO Postdoctoral Fellowship in Science] 1981-82\n* [https://researchtraining.nih.gov/programs/career-development Research Career Development Award], NIH, 1984-89<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchtraining.nih.gov/programs/career-development|title=Research Career Development Awards {{!}} Research Training and Career Development|website=researchtraining.nih.gov|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* [https://www.niddk.nih.gov/research-funding/process/apply/funding-mechanisms/k-awards/k01 ADAMHA Research Scientist Development Award, National Institute of Mental Health], 1989\u201394\n* [https://www.niddk.nih.gov/research-funding/process/apply/funding-mechanisms/k-awards/k01 ADAMHA Research Scientist Development Award, National Institute of Mental Health] 1994-99\n* Foreign Member, The [[Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters|Royal Norwegian society of Sciences and Letter]] (Natural Sciences), 2004\u2013present\n* [[National Institutes of Health MERIT Award|MERIT Award]], National Advisory Council on Aging, 2004\u201314\n* [[Regents\u2019 Professor|Regents Professor]], University of Arizona, 2006\u2013present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://facultyaffairs.arizona.edu/content/regents-professors|title=Regents' Professors {{!}} UA Faculty Affairs|website=facultyaffairs.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* Endowed Chair: Evelyn F. McKnight Chair Learning and Memory in Aging, 2006\u2013present\n* Fellow, [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]], 2007\u2013present\n** Fellows are elected annually by the AAAS council. Fellows are recognized for their contributions to the advancement of science or its application are scientifically or socially distinguished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaas.org/fellows|title=AAAS Honorary Fellows|website=American Association for the Advancement of Science|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* 2009 [https://www.apadivisions.org/division-6/awards/marquis APA Division 6 D.B. Marquis Behavioral Neuroscience Award], 2010\n* 2010 [https://www.apadivisions.org/division-6/awards/marquis APA Division 6 D.B. Marquis Behavioral Neuroscience Award for Behavioral Neuroscience]\n* [https://www.sfn.org/initiatives/awards/mika-salpeter-award Mika Salpeter Lifetime Achievement Award]. 2010<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [https://www.lpl.arizona.edu/graduate/awards/galileo Galileo Fellow], College of Science, University of Arizona, 2011\u2013present\n* [[Ralph W. Gerard Prize in Neuroscience|Ralph W Gerard Prize in Neuroscience]] (2013)\n* [https://www.apa.org/about/awards/scientific-contributions?tab=3 APA Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions] (2014)\n** Barnes received this award as her role as director of the McKnight Brain Institute, the role in which she currently holds. This award is considered to be one of the highest awards of the Society for Neuroscience.\n* Quad-L Award (2017)\n** Barnes being one of the 7 people (including herself) who holds this award. This award is for distinguished contemporary scientists actively involved in research in regard to learning, memory or cognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://embi.arizona.edu/news/2017/10/dr-barnes-receives-quad-l-award|title=Dr. Barnes receives the Quad-L Award {{!}} Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute|website=embi.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* MOCA Local Genius Award, 2017\n* Elected to [[National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Science]], 2018\n** This award is one of the highest honors. Barnes received this award for her distinguished and continuation of her original research.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Carol A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Riverside alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n[[Category:Carleton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the British broadcaster|Carol Barnes}}\n{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Carol A. Barnes\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = United States\n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Neuroscience]], [[memory]], [[learning]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Arizona]]\n| alma_mater = B.A., [[University of California, Riverside]] <br />\nM.A., [[University of Ottawa]] <br />Ph.D. [[Carleton University]] <br />postdoctoral training in neurophysiology at [[Dalhousie University]], [[University of Oslo]], and the Cerebral Functions Group at [[University College London]] \n| doctoral_advisor = Peter Fried\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Carol_A_Barnes.png|thumb|Carol A Barnes, PhD]]\n'''Carol A. Barnes, Ph.D.''' is a [[neuroscientist]] and a Regents' [[Professor]] of [[psychology]] at the [[University of Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol |title=Carol Barnes |publisher=Department of Psychology, University of Arizona |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525213406/http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since 2006, she has been the Evelyn F. McKnight Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |title=Evelyn F. McKnight Endowed Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date=2006-12-11 |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919034703/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |archive-date=2013-09-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and is director of the Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |title=McKnight Brain Institute at the University of Arizona |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195119/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barnes has been president of the [[Society for Neuroscience]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfn.org/about/volunteer-leadership/sfn-presidents |title=Society for Neuroscience - SfN Presidents |publisher=Society for Neuroscience |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> and is a [[Fellow of the AAAS|Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V |title=Fellows &#124; AAAS MemberCentral |publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525202502/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and foreign member of the [[Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |title=Utenlandske medlemmer naturvitenskapelig klass |publisher=Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters |accessdate=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222003839/http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |archivedate=2013-12-22 }}</ref> She was elected to the [[National Academy of Sciences]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasonline.org/news-and-multimedia/news/May-1-2018-NAS-Election.html|title=May 1 2018 NAS Election|first=National Academy of Sciences -|last=http://www.nasonline.org|website=www.nasonline.org}}</ref>\n\nBarnes has produced over 170 peer reviewed publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gruberprizes.org/SelectingRecipients/SelectionAdvisoryBoard_Bio.php?id=23 |title=The Gruber Foundation Homepage &#124; The Gruber Foundation |publisher=Gruberprizes.org |date=2014-03-03 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> Broadly, her research is focused on the neurophysiological and behavioral changes that occur in the brain during aging. Understanding of these changes may shed light on the processes that contribute to age-related neurodegenerative disorders such as [[Alzheimer's Disease]]. Barnes also developed the [[Barnes maze]], a spatial navigation memory task that is used to assess hippocampal-dependent memory.\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:Carleton_University_River.jpg|thumb|Carleton University River]]\n[[File:Riverside,_California_view_from_Box_Springs.jpg|thumb|Riverside, California view from Box Springs]]\n[[File:The_University_of_Oslo.jpg|thumb|The University of Oslo]]\n[[File:London_MMB_08_University_College.jpg|thumb|London MMB 08 University College]]\nCarol Barnes received a Bachelors of Arts in Psychology with honors at the [[University of California]], riverside, in 1971. She continued her education at [[Carleton University]] located in Ottawa Ontario, Canada, earning her Masters of Arts degree in Psychology in 1972.During her studies in pursuing a PhD in Psychology, Barnes took a temporary position as a postdoctoral researcher researching in [[neuropsychology]] and [[neurophysiology]] in the department of psychology at [[Dalhousie University]], at the institute of neurophysiology of [[University of Oslo]]as well as in Cerebral function at [[University College London|University College of London]]. In 1977 she graduated with Cum Laude in psychology at [[Carleton University]].\n\n== Career ==\nBarnes currently holds the positions of director for two organizations: the Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute and the Neural Systems-Memory and Aging. She is also the Endowed Chair of the Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute for Learning-Memory in Aging. Today, she is a regents professor at the [[University of Arizona]] in Tucson, Arizona,\u00a0of the BIO5 Institute, funded by the Technology and Research Fund (TRIF).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bio5.org/about/why|title=Why BIO5 {{!}} BIO5 Institute|website=bio5.org|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> At the BIO5 institute she works with students addressing [[Alzheimer's disease]] and other age-related brain diseases. Barnes also teaches cancer biology, neuroscience, psychology, and physiological sciences.\n\n== Research ==\nBarnes is involved with the [[neuroscience]] research community on a national and local level. Barnes research spans through 4 decades aiming to better understand the aging of the brain in relation to cognitive diseases. Her research is conducted by utilizing animal models such as primates and rats to explore and understand how memory is impacted through the normal aging process of the brain through means of neurobiological mechanisms that are involved. The use of animal models in Barnes research is translated into treatments used for abnormal functioning of the brain aimed at prolonging the cognitive lifespan of older individuals. The nature of Barnes research entails the use of behavioral, anatomical, [[Electrophysiology|electrophysiological]] and molecular techniques\u00a0 to further examine the implications of normal aging impacting brain functioning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.arizona.edu/users/carol-barnes|title=Carol Barnes {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.arizona.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Most areas of her research involves examining and observing the [[hippocampus]] structure in the brains of rats and monkeys, observing and recording\u00a0 synaptic transmission in cell to cell signaling, and genomic sequencing.\n\n=== [[Barnes maze|Barnes Maze]] ===\nTo study spatial learning and memory, Carol Barnes created her own maze to test whether rodents, specifically mice, could remember the location of an escape box on a platform. This test has become a standard method of memory testing in laboratories. Designed in 1979, Barnes' maze was an alternative to study memory without the use of external reward or punishment, while also reducing the stress put on the animal throughout the process.\n[[File:Barnes_maze.jpg|thumb|The Barnes maze]]\nThe original study consisted of a platform (122&nbsp;cm diameter) raised 91&nbsp;cm above the floor with 18 circular holes (9.5&nbsp;cm diameters) spaced evenly around the perimeter. Under one of the holes is a black escape box, or any dark color in contrast to the color of the platform; the rest of the holes lead to false escape boxes. The study consisted of 3 variations of the experiment. First, the mouse simply had to find the escape chamber that was placed under one of the holes. Second, the escape chamber was moved to a hole rotated 120-140 degrees from the original hole; the original hole was also covered. Third, the same method as the second variation was used except the original hole was not covered. Barnes and her team found that overall, male mice performed better in all variations of the experiment. Further, they found younger mice also performed better in all variations, while older mice demonstrated notable difficulties in variations 2 and 3. This showed aging impairment in spatial memory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gawel|first=Kinga|last2=Gibula|first2=Ewa|last3=Marszalek-Grabska|first3=Marta|last4=Filarowska|first4=Joanna|last5=Kotlinska|first5=Jolanta H.|date=2019-01-01|title=Assessment of spatial learning and memory in the Barnes maze task in rodents\u2014methodological consideration|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|journal=Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Archives of Pharmacology|language=en|volume=392|issue=1|pages=1\u201318|doi=10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|issn=1432-1912|pmc=6311199|pmid=30470917}}</ref>\n[[File:Hippocampus.png|thumb|Hippocampus]]\nSpatial memory corresponds to the functioning of the [[hippocampus]], while route learning involves the [[Striatum|striatal]] systems. Overall, rodents of various ages learned T-mazes within the same number of trials, but the strategies used to learn and remember mazes differed with age. Young rats predominately utilized \u201cplace\u201d strategies which rely upon [[Hippocampus|hippocampal]] functioning, while older rats relied upon \u201cresponse\u201d strategies. Using [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] imaging techniques, Barnes and her team were able to see that in normally aged brains of rodents, the size of the [[hippocampus]] did not change while the volume of [[Grey matter|cortical grey matter]] did. This animal model allowed an understanding of what the brain looks like during normal human functioning to compare it to brains that have been degenerated due to [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]] (rodents do not exhibit AD). These findings demonstrate that while during normal aging the [[hippocampus]] remains the same size, its function may decrease in comparison to functions of other areas of the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Samson|first=Rachel D.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2013|title=Impact of Aging Brain Circuits on Cognition|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3694726/|journal=The European journal of neuroscience|volume=37|issue=12|pages=1903\u20131915|doi=10.1111/ejn.12183|issn=0953-816X|pmc=3694726|pmid=23773059|via=}}</ref>\n\nLooking deeper into the tissue affected, single-cell imaging showed there were 3 main types of cells that make up the hippocampus. When observing cell activity and the number of cells of the hippocampus of rats, it was found that the [[CA1 neuron|CA1]] and [[CA3 region|CA3]] [[pyramidal cell]]s continued to be active and of the same volume. However, the number of [[granule cell]]s of the [[dentate gyrus]] continuously decreased with age; the function of these cells also declined leading Carol and her team to conclude these gyrus cells are the weak link of the hippocampal circuit involved in memory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barnes|first=Carol A.|date=2011-10-03|title=Secrets of aging: What does a normally aging brain look like?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3186042/|journal=F1000 Biology Reports|volume=3|doi=10.3410/B3-22|issn=1757-594X|pmc=3186042|pmid=22003369}}</ref>\n\nA few of Barnes\u2019s latest research publication was published in 2017 are:\u00a0 \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S016643281630420X Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in the macaque monkeys]\u201d, \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28174334 Evidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus]\u201d, and \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627317305615 The aging navigational system]\u201d.\n\n=== Primate Research ===\n[[File:Brain_regions_involved_in_memory_formation.jpg|thumb|Brain regions involved in memory formation]]\nIn addition to work on rodent models, Dr. Barnes has helped advance the field of normative aging research using nonhuman primate models, specifically [[Macaque|macaque monkeys]].\u00a0 Primarily, Barnes\u2019 early work in macaques helped to tie together neurobiological data collected from rodents and functional imaging data from older humans. In the paper \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4848213/ Memory impairment in aged primates is associated with region-specific network dysfunction]\u201d Barnes and her team showed that older monkeys had significant impairment on object recognition than younger monkeys. In addition, the older monkeys displayed a lower density of inhibitory somatostatin positive [[interneuron]]s in the [[CA3 region|CA3]] sub-region of the [[hippocampus]]. These [[interneuron]]s are responsible for regulating the activity of excitatory neurons in the [[hippocampus]]. With less [[interneuron]] density, the baseline firing rate of [[CA3 region|CA3]] excitatory neurons was elevated, which resembles the increased hippocampal activity shown in imaging studies of older human adults. Both a decrease in [[interneuron]] density and increase baseline firing rates in the [[hippocampus]] have been associated with poor cognition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2019-12-26|title=Experiments in macaque monkeys provide critical insights into age-associated changes in cognitive and sensory function|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6936691/|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=116|issue=52|pages=26247\u201326254|doi=10.1073/pnas.1902279116|issn=0027-8424|pmc=6936691|pmid=31871147}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in the paper \u201cEvidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus\u201d Dr. Barnes and her team found evidence that mammals require the same quantity of neurons in the hippocampus to encode memory of a single experience. This finding means that the studied rodents, nonhuman primates, and humans all use a stable amount of neurons to encode a similar virtual experience. However, since all three subjects have different sized hippocampi, the proportion of neurons used for the encoding of experience differ. Rodents have the smallest hippocampus and thus use 40% of their hippocampus neurons for encoding, nonhuman primates have larger hippocampi and use 4%, and finally humans have the largest hippocampi and use an estimated 2.5% for experiential encoding.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wixted|first=John T.|last2=Goldinger|first2=Stephen D.|last3=Squire|first3=Larry R.|last4=Kuhn|first4=Joel R.|last5=Papesh|first5=Megan H.|last6=Smith|first6=Kris A.|last7=Treiman|first7=David M.|last8=Steinmetz|first8=Peter N.|date=2018-01-30|title=Coding of episodic memory in the human hippocampus|url=https://www.pnas.org/content/115/5/1093|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=115|issue=5|pages=1093\u20131098|doi=10.1073/pnas.1716443115|issn=0027-8424|pmid=29339476|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nDr. Barnes has also done research to see how executive function changes with normative aging. [[Executive functions]] are the higher order process humans take part in such as attention, decision making, impulse control, and emotional control. Once again studying [[macaque]]s, Barnes and her team focused on two aspects of executive function, attentional monitoring and updating as well as set shifting. Attentional monitoring and updating are when the rules of a given situation change requiring a corresponding change in behavioral responses. For example, when two options are presented one is the correct initial choice. When the correct choice becomes the second option instead, attentional monitoring and updating help correct for the rule change and alter behavior. The change in behavior is mediated through a process of trial and error which helps associate desired outcomes with certain behaviors. Barnes and her team found that older monkeys needed a greater number of trials to accurately account for a rule change. Meaning, the executive system behind attentional monitoring and updating is impaired with aging. Secondly, [[Cognitive flexibility|set shifting]] is the ability to unconsciously shift attention between tasks while maintaining accuracy. In her research, Barnes presented macaque monkeys with an object recognition test of previously learned objects. She then presented interfering objects which required shifts between the object choice and evaluation of novel objects. Her results showed that older monkeys performed better on object recognition with interference than younger monkeys. Thus set shifting abilities seem to be maintained if not enhanced with aging. The most important discovery out of these studies, however, is that the two aspects of executive function, monitoring and updating and set shifting, were shown to be independent systems that are affected differently with age.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Smith|first2=Anne C.|last3=Burke|first3=Sara N.|last4=Gazzaley|first4=Adam|last5=Barnes|first5=Carol A.|date=2017-03-30|title=Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in macaque monkeys|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5493156/|journal=Behavioural brain research|volume=322|issue=Pt B|pages=329\u2013338|doi=10.1016/j.bbr.2016.06.056|issn=0166-4328|pmc=5493156|pmid=27368416}}</ref>\n\nA final research contribution of Carol A Barnes involves the study of spatial networks and spatial memories in aging [[macaque]]s. Barnes and her team studied brain activity in four different conditions for movement: cages, sitting, walking on a treadmill, and freely walking around space. The study found that younger macaques have distinct spatial networks for all four distinct conditions. However, older monkeys displayed less differentiated activity of spatial networks. Meaning, all conditions evoked activation of the same undifferentiated networks. This finding suggests dynamic network changes as a possible explanation for spatial cognition deficits. In other words, the spatial processing networks become less precise with age and may contribute to spatial memory loss or confusion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Engle|first=James R.|last2=Machado|first2=Christopher J.|last3=Permenter|first3=Michele R.|last4=Vogt|first4=Julie A.|last5=Maurer|first5=Andrew P.|last6=Bulleri|first6=Alicia M.|last7=Barnes|first7=Carol A.|date=2016-11-30|title=Network Patterns Associated with Navigation Behaviors Are Altered in Aged Nonhuman Primates|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/36/48/12217|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=36|issue=48|pages=12217\u201312227|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4116-15.2016|issn=0270-6474|pmid=27903730|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nBarnes interest of normative aging in the brain stems from her grandfather when she and her family noticed that his memory was declining.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sherva|first=Kara|date=2015|title=Carol Barnes: A Prominent Voice in the Neuroscience of Aging, and a Proponent of Women in Neuroscience|url=https://soundideas.pugetsound.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=soundneuroscience|journal=Sound Neuroscience: An Undergraduate Neuroscience Journal|volume=2|pages=|via=}}</ref> Furthermore, Barnes is included in the [https://neurotree.org/beta/tree.php?pid=547 Neuroscience Academic Family Tree] . Listed there are her mentors and mentees.\n\n== Supporting Women and the Underprivileged in Neuroscience ==\nCarol A Barnes has been lauded by her peers and the public for her outstanding work in promoting opportunities for women and the underprivileged in neuroscience. In 2010, she received the Mika Salpeter Lifetime Achievement Award<ref name=\":0\" /> which \u201crecognizes individuals with outstanding career achievements in neuroscience who have also actively promoted the professional advancement of women in neuroscience.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfn.org/initiatives/awards|title=Awards|website=www.sfn.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore she is an active participant in the [https://msrp.medicine.arizona.edu/programs/disadvantaged-high-school-student-research-program NIH Disadvantaged High School Student Research Program], [https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/pa-files/PAR-99-091.html Minority Access to Research Careers], and the [https://mcnair.njit.edu/ McNair Achievement Program]. Finally, in 2013 Barnes gave a keynote address at the [https://www.sfn.org/cwinrsvp Celebration of Women in Neuroscience] entitled \u201cThe Evolving Face of Neuroscience: Role of Women and Globalization.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and Honors: ==\n{{external|section|date=April 2020}}\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://embi.arizona.edu/barnes/honors-awards|title=Dr. Carol A. Barnes - Honors and Awards {{!}} Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute|website=embi.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/funding/education.jsp?fund_type=1 National science Foundation Summer Research Fellowship], 1969\n** This fellowship funds students or identity programs that are focused on education developments\n* [https://osap.gov.on.ca/OSAPPortal/en/A-ZListofAid/PRDR019245.html Ontario Graduate Fellowship], 1972\u201374\n** For students pursuing their graduate studies at Master\u2019s and doctoral levels. This is a merit-based scholarship for students a part of the Ontario Graduate program.\n* [https://www.nlm.nih.gov/ep/NRSAFellowshipGrants.html NIH National Research Service Award], 1979\u201381\n** For Postdoctoral students gaining research and clinical training in both MD/PhD or other dual-doctoral degree training program\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/pubs/2002/nsf02178/nsf02178.htm NATO Postdoctoral Fellowship in Science] 1981-82\n* [https://researchtraining.nih.gov/programs/career-development Research Career Development Award], NIH, 1984-89<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchtraining.nih.gov/programs/career-development|title=Research Career Development Awards {{!}} Research Training and Career Development|website=researchtraining.nih.gov|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* [https://www.niddk.nih.gov/research-funding/process/apply/funding-mechanisms/k-awards/k01 ADAMHA Research Scientist Development Award, National Institute of Mental Health], 1989\u201394\n* [https://www.niddk.nih.gov/research-funding/process/apply/funding-mechanisms/k-awards/k01 ADAMHA Research Scientist Development Award, National Institute of Mental Health] 1994-99\n* Foreign Member, The [[Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters|Royal Norwegian society of Sciences and Letter]] (Natural Sciences), 2004\u2013present\n* [[National Institutes of Health MERIT Award|MERIT Award]], National Advisory Council on Aging, 2004\u201314\n* [[Regents\u2019 Professor|Regents Professor]], University of Arizona, 2006\u2013present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://facultyaffairs.arizona.edu/content/regents-professors|title=Regents' Professors {{!}} UA Faculty Affairs|website=facultyaffairs.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* Endowed Chair: Evelyn F. McKnight Chair Learning and Memory in Aging, 2006\u2013present\n* Fellow, [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]], 2007\u2013present\n** Fellows are elected annually by the AAAS council. Fellows are recognized for their contributions to the advancement of science or its application are scientifically or socially distinguished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaas.org/fellows|title=AAAS Honorary Fellows|website=American Association for the Advancement of Science|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* 2009 [https://www.apadivisions.org/division-6/awards/marquis APA Division 6 D.B. Marquis Behavioral Neuroscience Award], 2010\n* 2010 [https://www.apadivisions.org/division-6/awards/marquis APA Division 6 D.B. Marquis Behavioral Neuroscience Award for Behavioral Neuroscience]\n* [https://www.sfn.org/initiatives/awards/mika-salpeter-award Mika Salpeter Lifetime Achievement Award]. 2010<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [https://www.lpl.arizona.edu/graduate/awards/galileo Galileo Fellow], College of Science, University of Arizona, 2011\u2013present\n* [[Ralph W. Gerard Prize in Neuroscience|Ralph W Gerard Prize in Neuroscience]] (2013)\n* [https://www.apa.org/about/awards/scientific-contributions?tab=3 APA Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions] (2014)\n** Barnes received this award as her role as director of the McKnight Brain Institute, the role in which she currently holds. This award is considered to be one of the highest awards of the Society for Neuroscience.\n* Quad-L Award (2017)\n** Barnes being one of the 7 people (including herself) who holds this award. This award is for distinguished contemporary scientists actively involved in research in regard to learning, memory or cognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://embi.arizona.edu/news/2017/10/dr-barnes-receives-quad-l-award|title=Dr. Barnes receives the Quad-L Award {{!}} Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute|website=embi.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n* MOCA Local Genius Award, 2017\n* Elected to [[National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Science]], 2018\n** This award is one of the highest honors. Barnes received this award for her distinguished and continuation of her original research.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Carol A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Riverside alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n[[Category:Carleton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n", "name_user": "8421nguyena", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carol_A._Barnes"}
{"title_page": "Olli Jalonen", "text_new": "{{Expand Finnish|topic=culture|date=July 2010|Olli Jalonen}}\n[[File:Olli Jalonen.jpg|thumb|right|300px]]\n'''Olli Jalonen''' (born February 21, 1954 in [[Helsinki]], is a [[Finland|Finnish]] author. He lives in H\u00e4meenlinna, Finland. He has studied Social Sciences (M.A. and L.Soc.Sc) and Literature (Ph.D) and has worked in journalism before becoming a full-time writer in 1981. His debut book was published in 1978 and since that he has published over 20 books (mostly novels and short story collections) and drama. Some of his novels have been translated into German, Swedish, Norwegian, Estonian and Latvian, and short stories in different languages.\n\nOlli Jalonen studied at the University of Tampere 1973-2006 and also at Trinity College Dublin 1979\u20131980. He took part in the International Writing Program IWP at the University of Iowa in 1982 and was the first Writer-in-Residence of Zurich, Switzerland, in 2010\u20132011. Olli Jalonen has received several literary awards since his debut book, including the [[Finlandia Fiction Prize]] in 1990 for his [[novel]] ''Is\u00e4ksi ja tytt\u00e4reksi'' and again in 2018 for his [[novel]] ''Taivaanpallo'', the J. H. Erkko Prize for the best debut book in 1978 and the Eino Leino Prize in 1990. He has had three nominations for the Nordic Council Literature Prize<ref>http://oga.otava.fi/authors/olli-jalonen/</ref><ref>The Dedalus Book of Finnish Fantasy, Dedalus 2005</ref><ref>http://www.uta.fi/lti/en/plural/theses/completed.html</ref><ref>http://www.writers-in-residence.ch/en/home/olli_jalonen</ref><ref>http://www.norden.org/en/nordic-council/nordic-council-prizes/nordisk-raads-litteraturpris</ref>\n\nIt has been said that Olli Jalonen's writing shows a delight in playing with the nature of reality. One of the trademarks of his work as a prosewriter is his desire to bring together his earlier works to form part of new, larger entities, thus making his texts comment upon one another.<ref>The Dedalus Book of Finnish Fantasy, Dedalus 2005</ref>\n\nFor decades he has been interested in the island of St. Helena and the astronomer and scientist Edmond Halley (1656-1742). For instance Jalonen's novel ''14 solmua Greenwichiin'' (14 Knots to Greenwich, Otava 2008) centres on the story of a fictional round-the-world race by land and sea that starts and ends in Greenwich. It moves between suspense fiction and autobiography in an unusual and often enigmatic way. The novel ''Taivaanpallo'' (The Celestial Sphere, Otava 2018) tells about the rays of the Enlightenment and life on St. Helena and London in the 1680s. The story of Edmond Halley and his trusted apprentice Angus continues in ''Merenpeitto'' (The Art of Living under Water, Otava 2019).<ref>http://www.booksfromfinland.fi/2008/12/olli-jalonen-14-solmua-greenwichiin-14-knots-to-greenwich/</ref><ref>http://nordicvoices.blogspot.fi/2009/03/14-knots-to-greenwich.html</ref><ref>https://rightsandbrands.com/products/the-celestial-sphere/</ref><ref>https://rightsandbrands.com/products/the-art-of-living-under-water/</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n===Novels and short story collections===\n* {{cite book | title=Unien tausta | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1978 | isbn = 951-1-04899-6}}\n* {{cite book | title=Sulkaturkki | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1979 | isbn = 951-1-05540-2}}\n* {{cite book | title=Ilo ja h\u00e4pe\u00e4 | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1981 | isbn = 951-1-06394-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Hotelli el\u00e4ville | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava  | year=1983 | isbn = 951-1-07472-5}}\n* {{cite book | title=Tuhkasaari | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1987 | isbn = 951-1-09814-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Johan ja Johan | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1989 | isbn = 951-1-10895-6}}\n* {{cite book | title=Is\u00e4ksi ja tytt\u00e4reksi | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1990 | isbn = 951-1-11475-1}}\n* {{cite book | title=El\u00e4m\u00e4, ja el\u00e4m\u00e4 | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1992 | isbn = 951-1-12178-2}}\n* {{cite book | title=Kenen kuvasta kerrot | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1996 | isbn = 951-1-14394-8}}\n* {{cite book | title=Yksityiset t\u00e4htitaivaat | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1999 | isbn = 951-1-15953-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Yhdeks\u00e4n pyramidia  | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2000 | isbn = 951-1-16639-5}}\n* {{cite book | title=V\u00e4rj\u00e4tty\u00e4 rakkautta | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2003 | isbn = 951-1-18841-0}}\n* {{cite book | title=14 solmua Greenwichiin | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2008 | isbn = 978-951-1-23014-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Poikakirja | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2010 | isbn = 978-951-1-24572-8}}\n* {{cite book | title=Karatolla | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2012 | isbn = 978-951-1-26469-9}}\n* {{cite book | title=Miehi\u00e4 ja ihmisi\u00e4 | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2014 | isbn = 978-951-1-28301-0}}\n* {{cite book | title=Taivaanpallo | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2018 | isbn = 978-951-1-31917-7}}\n* {{cite book | title=Merenpeitto | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2019 | isbn = 978-951-1-34512-1}}\n\n=== Other books ===\n* {{cite book | title=Matkailijan Irlanti (Jalonen, Olli & Jalonen, Riitta) | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1980 | isbn = 951-1-05785-5}}\n* {{cite book | title=Kansa kulttuurien virroissa. Tuontikulttuurin suuntia ja sis\u00e4lt\u00f6j\u00e4 Suomessa itsen\u00e4isyyden aikana | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1985 | isbn = 951-1-08392-9}}\n* {{cite book | title=Kymmenen vuosituhatta. Kertomuksia suomalaisten historiasta (Ojanen, Eero & Jalonen, Olli)| location=Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 | publisher=Atena | year=1999 | isbn = 951-796-175-8}}\n* {{cite book | title=Hitaasti kudotut nopeat hetket. Kirjoittamisen assosiaatiosta 1900-luvun suomalaisessa proosassa | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2006 | isbn = 951-1-21007-6}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jalonen, Olli}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Finnish professors]]\n[[Category:Finnish writers]]\n[[Category:International Writing Program alumni]]\n[[Category:Finlandia Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Eino Leino Prize]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Finnish|topic=culture|date=July 2010|Olli Jalonen}}\n[[File:Olli Jalonen.jpg|thumb|right|300px]]\n'''Olli Jalonen''' (born February 21, 1954 in [[Helsinki]], is a [[Finland|Finnish]] author. He lives in H\u00e4meenlinna, Finland. He has studied Social Sciences (M.A. and L.Soc.Sc) and Literature (Ph.D) and has worked in journalism before becoming a full-time writer in 1981. His debut book was published in 1978 and since that he has published over 20 books (mostly novels and short story collections) and drama. Some of his novels have been translated into German, Swedish, Norwegian, Estonian and Latvian, and short stories in different languages.\n\nOlli Jalonen studied at the University of Tampere 1973-2006 and also at Trinity College Dublin 1979-1980. He took part in the International Writing Program IWP at the University of Iowa in 1982 and was the first Writer-in-Residence of Zurich, Switzerland, in 2010-2011. Olli Jalonen has received several literary awards since his debut book, including the [[Finlandia Fiction Prize]] in 1990 for his [[novel]] ''Is\u00e4ksi ja tytt\u00e4reksi'' and again in 2018 for his [[novel]] ''Taivaanpallo'', the J. H. Erkko Prize for the best debut book in 1978 and the Eino Leino Prize in 1990. He has had three nominations for the Nordic Council Literature Prize<ref>http://oga.otava.fi/authors/olli-jalonen/</ref><ref>The Dedalus Book of Finnish Fantasy, Dedalus 2005</ref><ref>http://www.uta.fi/lti/en/plural/theses/completed.html</ref><ref>http://www.writers-in-residence.ch/en/home/olli_jalonen</ref><ref> http://www.norden.org/en/nordic-council/nordic-council-prizes/nordisk-raads-litteraturpris</ref>\n\nIt has been said that Olli Jalonen\u2019s writing shows a delight in playing with the nature of reality. One of the trademarks of his work as a prosewriter is his desire to bring together his earlier works to form part of new, larger entities, thus making his texts comment upon one another.<ref>The Dedalus Book of Finnish Fantasy, Dedalus 2005</ref>\n\nFor decades he has been interested in the island of St. Helena and the astronomer and scientist Edmond Halley (1656-1742). For instance Jalonen\u2019s novel ''14 solmua Greenwichiin'' (14 Knots to Greenwich, Otava 2008) centres on the story of a fictional round-the-world race by land and sea that starts and ends in Greenwich. It moves between suspense fiction and autobiography in an unusual and often enigmatic way. The novel ''Taivaanpallo'' (The Celestial Sphere, Otava 2018) tells about the rays of the Enlightenment and life on St. Helena and London in the 1680s. The story of Edmond Halley and his trusted apprentice Angus continues in ''Merenpeitto'' (The Art of Living under Water, Otava 2019).<ref>http://www.booksfromfinland.fi/2008/12/olli-jalonen-14-solmua-greenwichiin-14-knots-to-greenwich/</ref><ref>http://nordicvoices.blogspot.fi/2009/03/14-knots-to-greenwich.html</ref><ref>https://rightsandbrands.com/products/the-celestial-sphere/</ref><ref> https://rightsandbrands.com/products/the-art-of-living-under-water/</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n===Novels and short story collections===\n* {{cite book | title=Unien tausta | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1978 | isbn = 951-1-04899-6}}\n* {{cite book | title=Sulkaturkki | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1979 | isbn = 951-1-05540-2}}\n* {{cite book | title=Ilo ja h\u00e4pe\u00e4 | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1981 | isbn = 951-1-06394-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Hotelli el\u00e4ville | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava  | year=1983 | isbn = 951-1-07472-5}}\n* {{cite book | title=Tuhkasaari | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1987 | isbn = 951-1-09814-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Johan ja Johan | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1989 | isbn = 951-1-10895-6}}\n* {{cite book | title=Is\u00e4ksi ja tytt\u00e4reksi | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1990 | isbn = 951-1-11475-1}}\n* {{cite book | title=El\u00e4m\u00e4, ja el\u00e4m\u00e4 | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1992 | isbn = 951-1-12178-2}}\n* {{cite book | title=Kenen kuvasta kerrot | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1996 | isbn = 951-1-14394-8}}\n* {{cite book | title=Yksityiset t\u00e4htitaivaat | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1999 | isbn = 951-1-15953-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Yhdeks\u00e4n pyramidia  | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2000 | isbn = 951-1-16639-5}}\n* {{cite book | title=V\u00e4rj\u00e4tty\u00e4 rakkautta | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2003 | isbn = 951-1-18841-0}}\n* {{cite book | title=14 solmua Greenwichiin | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2008 | isbn = 978-951-1-23014-4}}\n* {{cite book | title=Poikakirja | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2010 | isbn = 978-951-1-24572-8}}\n* {{cite book | title=Karatolla | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2012 | isbn = 978-951-1-26469-9}}\n* {{cite book | title=Miehi\u00e4 ja ihmisi\u00e4 | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2014 | isbn = 978-951-1-28301-0}}\n* {{cite book | title=Taivaanpallo | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2018 | isbn = 978-951-1-31917-7}}\n* {{cite book | title=Merenpeitto | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2019 | isbn = 978-951-1-34512-1}}\n\n=== Other books ===\n* {{cite book | title=Matkailijan Irlanti (Jalonen, Olli & Jalonen, Riitta) | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1980 | isbn = 951-1-05785-5}}\n* {{cite book | title=Kansa kulttuurien virroissa. Tuontikulttuurin suuntia ja sis\u00e4lt\u00f6j\u00e4 Suomessa itsen\u00e4isyyden aikana | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=1985 | isbn = 951-1-08392-9}}\n* {{cite book | title=Kymmenen vuosituhatta. Kertomuksia suomalaisten historiasta (Ojanen, Eero & Jalonen, Olli)| location=Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 | publisher=Atena | year=1999 | isbn = 951-796-175-8}}\n* {{cite book | title=Hitaasti kudotut nopeat hetket. Kirjoittamisen assosiaatiosta 1900-luvun suomalaisessa proosassa | location=Helsinki | publisher=Otava | year=2006 | isbn = 951-1-21007-6}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jalonen, Olli}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Finnish professors]]\n[[Category:Finnish writers]]\n[[Category:International Writing Program alumni]]\n[[Category:Finlandia Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Eino Leino Prize]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2), 1979-1980 \u2192 1979\u20131980 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olli_Jalonen"}
